    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-04-24T18:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-04-24T18:36:00-05:00" n="662"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d662">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">814.00/447: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McMillin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-04-24T17:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 24, 1920—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 26—12:19 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>82. Department’s 39, April 16, 6 p.m. The time not yet opportune to make
                    suggestions looking to Cabrera’s leaving Guatemala. Provisional Government is
                    holding him prisioner within the city pending full investigation of his
                    presumably large estate, claiming much <pb facs="0843" n="753" xml:id="pg_753"/>
                    of it belongs to Guatemala. They fear public wrath if he is permitted to leave.
                    There are reports he will be tried for crime, but nothing positive. City and
                    country rapidly approaching normal.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">McMillin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
